{# ── GROSS-VS-NET TABLE · vs-scroll + vs-table (no collapse, T3). Carries the gross-vs-net body prose. ── #}
<section class="section" id="acctind-agency-comparison">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">The most consequential accounting decision an agency makes</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Gross revenue presentation vs. net revenue presentation.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">For media-heavy and production-heavy agencies, the gross-vs-net question changes apparent revenue by 5&ndash;10&times; and every margin metric with it. Here&rsquo;s what the same agency looks like under each presentation &mdash; and why most agencies should be on net.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="vs-scroll">
      <table class="vs-table">
        <caption class="sr-only">Gross vs. net revenue presentation for agencies</caption>
        <thead><tr><th scope="col">Same agency, two presentations</th><th scope="col">Gross (agency-as-principal)</th><th scope="col" class="vs-table__us">Net (agency-as-agent &mdash; most common)</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><th scope="row">Example: $1M media + $150K fee</th><td><span class="vs-table__concede">Revenue $1,150,000 &middot; COGS $1,000,000 &middot; Gross profit $150,000</span></td><td class="vs-table__us"><span class="vs-table__concede">Revenue $150,000 &middot; no pass-through in revenue or COGS &middot; Gross profit $150,000</span></td></tr>
          <tr><th scope="row">ASC 606 framework</th><td><span class="vs-table__concede">Agency controls media before transfer; takes inventory risk; full pricing discretion</span></td><td class="vs-table__us"><span class="vs-table__concede">Agency arranges for media; supplier controls until placed; limited or no inventory risk</span></td></tr>
          <tr><th scope="row">Apparent revenue</th><td><span class="vs-table__concede">Inflated 5&ndash;10&times; for media-heavy agencies</span></td><td class="vs-table__us"><span class="vs-table__concede">Reflects actual economic earnings &mdash; matches AGI</span></td></tr>
          <tr><th scope="row">Gross margin %</th><td><span class="vs-table__concede">Distorted: 13% on $1.15M of &ldquo;revenue&rdquo;</span></td><td class="vs-table__us"><span class="vs-table__concede">100% on $150K of true revenue</span></td></tr>
          <tr><th scope="row">Industry benchmarking</th><td><span class="vs-table__concede">Incompatible with industry data (Adweek, AdAge, 4A&rsquo;s, RECMA all report AGI)</span></td><td class="vs-table__us"><span class="vs-table__concede">Matches industry-standard reporting; benchmarks become usable</span></td></tr>
          <tr><th scope="row">Fundraise / M&amp;A diligence</th><td><span class="vs-table__concede">Buyer or investor immediately restates to net; trust eroded</span></td><td class="vs-table__us"><span class="vs-table__concede">Survives diligence cleanly; an agency-sophistication signal</span></td></tr>
          <tr><th scope="row">When gross is actually correct</th><td><span class="vs-table__concede">Agency holds inventory, sets retail price, takes the loss if unsold</span></td><td class="vs-table__us"><span class="vs-table__concede">Most agency engagements fail the principal test; net is the default</span></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="prose"><small>The principal-vs-agent analysis is performed engagement by engagement under ASC 606, not at the agency level &mdash; an agency may operate as principal on some work (production-buyout deals where it owns the deliverable) and agent on others (media buys, talent fees, third-party software resale). The chart of accounts handles both cleanly with clear separation.</small></p>
  </div>
</section>

